        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
Spectral settings: We center our spectral window at the N2H+ (3-2) rest frequency of 279.512 GHz with spectral window bandwidths of 234.375 MHz (smoothed resolution of 0.131 km/s). The expected line width is a few km/s, and so this resolution will be sufficient for us to model the velocity field of the emission line.  The source heliocentric velocities are also well known (to within a few km/s). The remaining spectral windows are used to obtain continuum.

Sensitivity: To estimate the expected N2H+ line fluxes and continuum flux densities per beam, we scaled the integrated line intensity obtained by Qi et al. 2013 for TW Hya to the appropriate distances to our targets, and adjusted the surface brightness to account for the size of the ring. (Because the N2H+ ring traces the CO condensation front, the temperature of the emission should be the same for all targets).  The expected line fluxe densities are shown in Table 1.   The expected line widths are a few km/s, and we desire a SNR of 5 at the line peak.  For RNO 90, DR Tau, FZ Tau and VW Cha, in that order, we request sensitivities of 20, 6, 6 and 6 mJy in a 0.1 km/s channel, though both FZ Tau and VW Cha may not achieve the SNR ~ 5 (the OT reports SNR ~ 2.7 for exposure times ~ 12 h)(Note that the sensitivity of the successful Qi et al. 2013 TW Hya observations was 30 mJy in a 0.1 km/s channel).


Spatial resolution: The required angular resolution depends on the distance to the disks and the predicted radius of the CO condensation front.  For all of our targets, the diameter of the expected CO condensation front divided by the distance implies a ring diameter of ~1.1-1.2 arcsec (see Table 1).  We therefore choose a desired angular resolution of 0.25 arcsec for all of our targets, in order to obtain a few resolution elements across the N2H+ ring.  </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
