    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>The efficiency of planetesimal formation depends on the amount of condensed volatiles in the midplane of protoplanetary disks. Snow lines mark the radial boundaries between water vapor and ice. H2O snow lines vary dynamically with disk structure and evolution and help constrain the water content, distribution and the type of planets that form within and beyond its location. ALMA offers the unprecedented ability to resolve the CO snow line, using emission from N2H+ as a chemical probe of the absence of CO gas in the midplane beyond the CO condensation front. We propose to determine the CO snow line for four classical disks and to compare these results with their H2O snow lines. These measurements provide a new way to study the water distribution in young disks. We want to determine if the CO midplane condensation front is predictive of the H2O snow line. If the CO front is truly a snow line its location should increase with stellar luminosity and water snow line location. No clear correlation between the locations may indicate an alternative scenario, perhaps that the water distribution is dominated by gas phase chemistry rather than freeze out.
</prp:abstract>
